<p>HUMAN RIGHTS COUNCIL 
Second session 
Agenda item 2 
</p>
<p><b>IMPLEMENTATION OF GENERAL ASSEMBLY RESOLUTION 60/251 
OF 15 MARCH 2006 ENTITLED &#8220;HUMAN RIGHTS COUNCIL&#8221; 
</b></p>
<p><b>Rights of the child:  draft President&#8217;s statement 
</b></p>
<p> <i>The Human Rights Council</i>, 
</p>
<p> 1. <i>Reaffirms</i> the Convention on the Rights of the Child and the Optional Protocols 
thereto on the sale of children, child prostitution and child pornography, and on the involvement 
of children in armed conflict; 
</p>
<p> 2.<i> Recalls</i> resolution 2005/44 of 19 April 2005 of the Commission on Human 
Rights; 
</p>
<p> 3. <i>Stresses</i> the importance of incorporating a strong child-rights perspective 
throughout its work; 
</p>
<p> 4. <i>Stresses also</i> that effective and enforced criminalization, educational programmes 
and awareness-raising activities are important in preventing and combating the sexual 
exploitation of children and reaffirms the need to continue to address the question of the demand 
factor in the commercial sexual exploitation of children as well as aspects related to prevention 
and rehabilitation of child victims of sexual exploitation; 
</p>
<p>GE.06-14981  (E)    201106 </p>

 <p> 
</p>
<p> 5. <i>Reaffirms</i> the need to continue to incorporate specific rights of the child concerns 
in relation to armed conflict into the Council&#8217;s discussions and resolutions, as well as into 
technical cooperation programmes of the Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for 
Human Rights, including increased awareness of the six grave child rights violations identified 
by the Secretary-General,<b>1</b> and emphasizes that the United Nations human rights system plays an 
essential role in ensuring the protection of the rights of war-affected children on the ground, 
including in the prevention of the use of child soldiers in armed conflicts, the release of abducted 
children, their reintegration and rehabilitation, taking into account the rights and the specific 
needs and capacities of girls; 
</p>
<p> 6. <i>Welcomes</i> the participatory and consultative process in preparation of the 
Secretary-General&#8217;s study on the question of the violence against children (A/61/299) in close 
collaboration with Member States and United Nations bodies and organizations, other relevant 
intergovernmental and non-governmental organizations and, in particular, the unprecedented 
level and quality of participation by children, and decides to continue to consider the question of 
violence against children and to hold a substantive discussion on the Secretary-General&#8217;s study 
on violence against children during its fourth session. 
</p>
<p>----- 
</p>
<p>                                                 
</p>
<p><b>1
</b>  See A/59/695-S/2005/72. </p>

